author: John Lund / Staff writer
title: HS FOOTBALL: Honesdale at Tunkhannock
text:
Sign Up Text Alerts | newsletter 
TUNKHANNOCK — For the first time in 21 games, Tunkhannock is in the win column. 
The Tigers used an efficient passing attack to balance a punishing running game that accounted for five touchdowns in a 40-8 win over Honesdale in a nonconference game Friday night at Tunkhannock Memorial Stadium. 
Tunkhannock (1-4) had 379 total yards and held the Hornets to just 100 total yards. 
Tunkhannock quarterback Logan Cywinski connected on three passes for 43 yards during an 11-play drive and capped it with a 4-yard touchdown run to put the Tigers up, 7-0, with 9:06 left in the second quater. 
Honesdale (2-3) would answer on its next drive when Clay Hewlett found Cris Vlacich in the corner of the endzone for a 27-yard touchdown. Hewlett’s 2-point pass gave the Hornets an 8-7 lead with 5:55 left in the first half. 
But the Tigers stole the momentum as Ryan Cywinski barreled through tacklers and returned the ensuing kickoff 82 yards for a touchdown and a 14-8 lead. 
He would find the end zone again on Tunkhannock’s next drive on a 9-yard run to extend the lead to 21-8 with 2:05 left before halftime. 
“I’ve never had this feeling before,” Ryan said. “Senior year and a 21-game losing streak — to finally break that is an amazing feeling, especially with my brother. I couldn’t have done it without him, or without my linemen. It’s not me just making the plays, it’s the whole team.” 
After Ryan Cywinski ended an 11-play drive to start the third quarter with a 3-yard touchdown run, his brother found the endzone with a 6-yard run of his own to extend Tunkhannock’s lead to 33-8 with 10:40 left in the game. 
The Tigers then caused a fumble on the ensuing kickoff and quickly capitalized when Logan scored his third touchdown of the night, this time from 6-yards out, to put the game away. 
Logan finished the game with 143 yards on the ground and added 115 through the air, while Ryan rushed for 95 yards and caught two passes for 39 more. 
“We thought our kids would have a little bit of confidence and desire coming in, but I think we came in a little overconfident,” Honesdale head coach Mike Jurkowski said. “We as coaches took Tunkhannock a little bit for granted and they played really hard and took it to us.
